29 sed felicius quia illos fecisse panciores sciunt: Itis in such epigrammatie phrases as this and others (e. g. c. 18 827 1212 1315 18 10 23 17 27 11 37 21138 40 25) that we may recognise the future author of the Historias and Annals Cp. Proleg. xlii n. 82.

30 videtur mihi iuter Menenios et Appios studuisse: On the style of Asinius Pollio, cf. the very similar observation of Quint. X 1, 113 a nitore et iucunditate Ciceronis ita longe abest ut videri potest saeculo prior. It is remarkable that Asinius, not unlike Seneca in this respect, was so blind to his own faults as to censure others for the very stylistic peculiarities which were conspicuous in his own writings. Cf. Sueten. de gramm. p. 108 de eodem (se. Ateio l’hilologo) Asinius Pollio in libro quo Sallustii scripta repre- hendit ut nimiu priscumne verborum adfectatione 001110.
